{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f4b89e44-4be3-4ab5-ab81-a625aaa6f26d","content":"You have two good options:\n\n## Option 1 — `Directory.Build.targets` with `IsTestProject` (recommended)\n\nMove the test-only properties to **`Directory.Build.targets`** instead of `.props`. By the time `.targets` is evaluated, the MSTest NuGet package has already set `IsTestProject` to `true`:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Directory.Build.targets -->\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"'$(IsTestProject)' == 'true'\">\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis works because MSBuild import order is: `Sdk.props` → `Directory.Build.props` → project file → NuGet `.props` (sets `IsTestProject`) → NuGet `.targets` → `Directory.Build.targets` → `Sdk.targets`.\n\n## Option 2 — Naming convention in `Directory.Build.props`\n\nIf you prefer keeping everything in `.props`, condition on project name:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Directory.Build.props -->\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$(MSBuildProjectName.EndsWith('.Tests'))\">\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Why not `IsTestProject` in `.props`?** — `Directory.Build.props` is imported *before* NuGet package props, so `IsTestProject` hasn't been set yet.\n\n**Option 1** is more robust since it works regardless of naming conventions. Option 2 is simpler but breaks if any test project doesn't follow the `.Tests` suffix pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b93cc8f5-4e0f-410f-9ed7-8c830f7d5e21","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to conditionally set MSBuild properties in a `Directory.Build.props` file so they only apply to test projects (not production/library projects) when migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP).\n\nThis is a knowledge question about MSBuild conditions. The standard approach is to use an MSBuild condition that detects whether a project references MSTest (or another test framework). There are a few common approaches:\n\n1. Use `Condition=\"'$(IsTestProject)' == 'true'\"` — but this property isn't automatically set.\n2. Use a naming convention like `Condition=\"$(MSBuildProjectName.EndsWith('.Tests'))\"`.\n\n\n3. Rely on the `IsTestProject` property that gets set automatically when you reference test-related packages like MSTest or Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nThe most reliable approach is to condition on `IsTestProject` being true, which the test SDKs set automatically, or fall back to a naming convention if that property isn't available. I'm setting up an example that shows how to wrap test-specific properties like `OutputType` and `EnableMSTestRunner` in a conditional block.\n\nNow I'm realizing that `IsTestProject` depends on which packages you have referenced — `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` sets it, but in newer MSTest versions (3.x+), just referencing the `MSTest` package itself is enough to trigger this property. So the approach should work reliably as long as you're using a modern test framework package.\n\nBut there's a timing issue here: `Directory.Build.props` runs before the NuGet package props are imported, which means `IsTestProject` won't be available yet when I'm trying to condition on it. I should use `Directory.Build.targets` instead, since that runs after all the package imports and property definitions are complete. Alternatively, I could fall back on a naming convention check in `Directory.Build.props` if I need to keep everything in one place. Directory.Build.props won't work reliably since `IsTestProject` from NuGet packages isn't available yet. I could use `Directory.Build.targets` instead where that property is set, or rely on a naming convention like checking if the project name ends with `.Tests`. The cleanest approach is probably convention-based in `Directory.Build.props`...\n\nWriting configuration code... I need to verify the exact import order for SDK-style projects. The NuGet-generated files and Directory.Build.props interact in a specific sequence, and I want to make sure I have it right before deciding between the two options. Let me trace through what Microsoft.Common.props actually does and when the NuGet restore files get imported relative to Directory.Build.props. I see that `Directory.Build.targets` is the right place since `IsTestProject` from NuGet packages is available by then, so I can set the test-related properties conditionally without needing a naming convention workaround.\n\nNow I'm considering the alternative approach using a naming convention in `Directory.Build.props` if they prefer to keep everything in one place, checking whether project names end with `.Tests` to identify test projects.","outputTokens":2475,"requestId":"0C03:2B0E8:267DF4:2D1A05:69F006BB"},"id":"0d3158fc-64db-411a-8d86-fd0fb4b7d70c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:01:28.813Z","parentId":"dbed49cf-68d5-4175-acd9-f8394e6b15b2"}
